      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes sense. so if there are risks like fraud or someone defaulting, how does the third party actually prevent that? like what triggers them to give the money to the seller vs keeping it in the account?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The third party, such as an escrow company or a bank, has a set of predefined conditions outlined in the escrow agreement that must be met before the funds are released to the seller. These conditions typically include:\n\n1. **Proof of Funds**: The buyer must provide proof of sufficient funds to cover the purchase price.\n2. **Title Search and Insurance**: The title search must confirm that the seller has a clear title to the property, and the buyer must secure title insurance.\n3. **Home Inspection**: The buyer must have completed a satisfactory home inspection.\n4. **Appraisal**: The property must appraise for at least the purchase price.\n5. **Loan Approval**: The buyer must have secured a mortgage or other financing approval.\n6. **Closing Documents**: All necessary legal documents, including the deed and mortgage, must be prepared and signed.\n\nThe third party will only release the funds to the seller once all these conditions are met. If any of these conditions are not satisfied, the third party will withhold the funds until the issue is resolved. This process helps to mitigate the risks of fraud or default by ensuring that the transaction is completed according to the agreed-upon terms and that both parties are protected.",
      "source": "target",
